  (financial domain familiarity)

### Q1 answer framework (required by the posting)
"The largest structured file I've processed in production was [context from
TDAAS data pipeline work / describe SQL-backed ETL at U.S. Bank]. For large XML
specifically, I use lxml's iterparse with explicit element clearing: parse one
element at a time, process it, call elem.clear() and also clear preceding
siblings via root[0].clear() after each batch to prevent the tree from
accumulating in memory. This keeps resident memory at the size of one element
subtree rather than the full document. I would demonstrate this approach in the
Milestone 2 PoC with a real memory profile attached."

### Q2 answer framework (required by the posting)
Layer by layer:
1. API middleware: on every request, extract tenant_id from the JWT, bind it to
   the request context, and reject any request missing it
2. Repository layer: every database query function signature takes tenant_id as
   a required argument and appends WHERE tenant_id = :tenant_id -- this is not
   optional or caller-controlled
3. PostgreSQL Row Level Security: RLS policies on every tenant-scoped table
   enforce isolation at the database engine level, so even a SQL injection that
   bypasses the application layer cannot read another tenant's rows
4. Optional: separate PostgreSQL schemas per tenant (stronger but more
   operationally complex -- a configuration choice at project kickoff)
5. Test suite: an automated test for every major entity that performs a
   cross-tenant read as Tenant A and asserts zero rows returned when data
   belongs only to Tenant B

