## 4. STRIPE SUBSCRIPTION MODEL DETAILS
(For accurate prose in the cover letter and deck)

### How Stripe subscriptions work (for this SaaS context)

**Products and Prices:**
- Create one Product per plan tier (e.g. "Starter", "Professional", "Enterprise")
- Each Product has one or more Price objects (monthly / annual)
- Price stores unit_amount (in cents), currency, and trial_period_days

**Trial:**
- Set trial_period_days on the Price object (e.g. 14)
- Subscription status is "trialing" -- no charge during trial
- Moves to "active" on first successful charge after trial

**Key webhooks the backend must handle:**
- invoice.paid: provision or continue access
- invoice.payment_failed: set status to past_due, email user
- customer.subscription.created: initial provisioning
- customer.subscription.updated: handle plan change / cancellation schedule
- customer.subscription.deleted: revoke access (both immediate and end-of-period)

**Proration on plan change:**
- Stripe auto-calculates credit for unused time on old plan
- Preview via POST /v1/invoices/create_preview before confirming change
- Apply via PUT /v1/subscriptions/{id} with new price_id

**Cancellation:**
- Immediate: DELETE /v1/subscriptions/{id} -- status becomes "canceled" now
- End of period: update subscription with cancel_at_period_end: true --
  status stays "active" until period end, then "canceled"
- Once canceled, cannot reactivate -- create new subscription on same customer

**Lifecycle states:** incomplete, trialing, active, past_due, canceled, unpaid

**Python/FastAPI integration pattern:**
- stripe Python library
- Webhook signature verification via stripe.Webhook.construct_event()
- Store stripe_customer_id and stripe_subscription_id on the tenant record
- Background job or webhook handler updates tenant status in DB

